re two\nwholo crops and a part of a third\nstill unsold and in the hands of tho\nEquity Society, consequently they do\nnot intend to add another crop to tho\nexisting surplus and are upholding\nIK the \"no crop\" idea.\nProper Easter Clothes\nAT PROPER PRICES\nOur reputation for first class Merchandise assures\nour customers only the newest and best the market\naffords, and our lowest prices makes an ideal combination.\nEASTER DRESS GOODS\nFor Ladies and Children.\nWe have made special preparations for Easter trade and we arc\nable to show you a complete stock ot\nDress Goods, Silks, White Goods, Wash\nGoods, Ginghams Laces, Embroideries.\nNovelties for All Ladies.\nEaster\nHosiery\nand Gloves\nLong\nGloves\nSee Our Great Stock of\nEaster\nBlack and Colored j Neckwear\nrifncc nHe Belts i\nWE CAN SUIT YOU\nWE CAN SAVE YOU MONEY\nand\nIMoxclties\nSHOES\nYANDELL-GUGENHEIM COMPANY\nRut iu tin., the Stenmrini; dis\ndistrict there is not a hand of tobacco\nuusold and the Society is therefore\nactually encouraging it members to\ngrow tobacco, but insisting at the\nsame time that the crops planted bo\nof such size that they cau be carefully\ntended so that a superior grade of\ntobacco may be raised.\nNo grower of tobacco in this county\nneed apprehend any danger in\nplanting a crop.\nCrittenden county has been done a\nvery grave injustice by sthe Courier-Journal\nand in it-. Princeton, Ky.,\ncorrespondent by giving currency to\na report to the effect that a secret\norganization had been formed in the\ncounty for the purpose of invading\nCaldwell county and inflicting damage\nupon that county or some one of\nits citizens or property.\nDoubtless no report was ever cir-J\neulated with less of fact or foundation\nupon which to base it.\nWe dare say there is not a citizen\nof this county who wishes ill, or\nwho would do evil to Caldwell county\nor any part or parcel of it.\nNothing but kindest of feelings\nhave ever prevailed between the people\nof the two counties, and the idea\nthat any set of men in this county\nwould organize for an attack upon\ntheir neighbors and kinsman of Caldwell\ncounty is preposterous.\nThe continued friendship and\ngoodwill of Caldwell county is of too\nmuch value for us to sutler it jeopardized\nwithout resentment and in our\nopinion, to give circulation to the\nreport is a crime second in degree\nonly to the putting into effect of the\nthreat to which the report gives credence.\nGeneral Business Outlook.\nSentiment is more hopeful and the\nreason thereof is based on the fact\nthat the foundation for better business\nis being laid with more regard\nfor security and stability. Impartial\nopinion lately leans more to to the\noptimistic view, and good judges of\nconditions profess to discover brightening\nprospects in various markets.\nWe havo passed through months of\nexcessive depression in financial and\ncommercial circles, and there is a\nconfident feeling that the country\nJt .r\nwill gradually draw awaj from discouraging\ninfluences. There may be\nalternate periods of fear and hope\nbefore we enter upon another era of\npernament betterment in business\nand induscry, but the trend is toward\nimprovement if developments continue\nfavorable. Broadly speaking,\nit may be said that the growth of\nnew confidence will prove a most effective\nlever to bring about conditions\nof strcngh and prosperity.\nMoney is easier, and there is a large\nsupply of loanable funds on thoroughly\nsound collateral, If there\nis no setback to the agricultural\noutlook demand for merchandise\nand labor should revive, and with\nthe season for outdoor work at hand\nthe inclination for activity in all\ndirections is expected to spread. We\nshould be prepared, however, for frequent\nspurts and reactions before\nmarkets generally rest on a sound\nand normal basts. It is still the\npart of wisdom to be conservative,\nbut not so absolutely ultra-conservative\nas to stand still and do nothing.\nWhen the tide turns don't try to oppose\nit, but turn with it.\nMoney to Loan.\nI have some money to loan, on first\nclass real estate, at per cent per\nannum. Inquire at this office or address\nP. 0. Box No. H.'J,\nMarion, Ky.\nKeep on Heepln' On,\n\"If the day looks kinder gloomy\nAn' your chances kinder slim,\nIf the situation's puzzlin'\nAn' the prospects awful grim,\nAn' perplexities keep prcssin'\nTill all hope is nearly gone,\nJus' hristle up and grit your tooth,\nand keep on keepiu' ou.\"\n.-v\nWMMM\nif \"T ,,,,il\nFor Exchange.\nI have throe head of good work\nmules to exchango for horses.\nOuVKtt HtJBLEV.\nNotice.\nHaving sold my Jack, \"Frank,\" to\nOrdway Lamb, who will stand him\nat Frcdonia, I wish my friends to\nknow where he can be found to save\nthem troublo of coming to my house.\nW. L. Huoheb,\nMarion, K.\nDon! Slop my Taper.\nThe recent ruling of the postotlice\ndepartment has caused the following\nfine old poem to start on the rounds\nagain\nDon't stop my paper, printer,\nDon't strike my name oil yet,\nYou know the times are stringent\nAnd dollars hard to get,\nHut tug a little harder,\nIs what I mean to do,\nAnd scrape the dimes together.\nEnough for me and you.\nI can't find to drop it,\nI find it doesn't pay,\nTo do without a paper\nHowever others may;\nI hate to ask my neighbors\nTo give me theirs on loan,\nThey don't just fcay, but mean it,\nWhy don't you have your own.\nYou can't tell how we miss it,\nIf it, by any late,\nShould happen not to reach us,\nOr come a little late;\nThen all is in a hubbub\nAnd things all go awry,\nAnd printer, it you're married,\nou know tho reason why.\nThen take it kinkly, printer,\nIf pay be somewhat slow,\nFor cash is not so plenty,\nAnd wants, not few you know,\nHut I must have my paper,\nCost what it may to me;\nI'd rather dock my sugar\nAnd do without my tea.\nSo, printer, don't you stop it,\nUnless you want my frowu,\nFor here's year subscription\nAnd credit it right down,\nAnd send the paper promptly\nAnd regularly on,\nAnd let it bring us often\nIt welcome bension.\nKx\n\"Health Coffee\" is really the closest\nCoffee Immitation ever yet produced.\nThis clever Coffee Substitute was recently\npropuced by Shoop of Racine,\nWis. Not a grain of real Coffo in it\neither. Dr. Snoop's Health CofTee is\nmade from pure toasted grains, with\nmalt nuts, etc. Really it would fool\nan expert who might drink it for\nCofTee. No '20 or 30 minutes tedious\nboiling. \"Made in a minute\" Hays the\ndoctor. Sold by Morris Yates.\nAtler Twenty-Nine kars.\n\"For ears I have\nbotu at mtenals a great uutlcrer\nfrom rheumatism, wrttos James\nHyde, of Heebe, Arl. \"Dunui;\nthat time I used gallons of various\nkinds of linimun'.s and oil.-, but got\nvory little relief. Tho attael woro\nso bad that I was often confined to\nmy bed helpless for weeks and months\nat a time.\n\"Not long ago, while sulloring\nfrom a scvorc attack, a sample bottle\nof Sloan s Liniment was sent to mc\nfor trial. My surprise was groat\nwhen I found that it irave mc instant\nrelief, and 1 immediately ordered\ntwo large bottles. I havo used\nabout a half of one fifty-cent bottle,\nand fcol so well that 1 want everybody\natilictcd as I was to know what\nSloan's Liniment hat; done for mo,\nand I shall always have a fooling of\ngratitude for the man who sent me\nthe sample bottle.\nMr. and Mrs. 01 Tucker, of Marion,\nand Mr. and Mrs Will McKlrov,\nof Princeton, spent Sunday with Mr.\nand Mrs. II. C. Hice.\nMiss Gcargia Boa? is visiting relatives\nin Livingston county.\nRev. Andres preached at tho\nChurch Sunday morning and\nevening.\nSeveral from fiorc attondoa the\nopera at Princeton Tuesday night.\nProf. Crow visited rolativos at\nPrinceton Saturday and Sunday.\nMrs, Willis Ray is visiting rolativci!\nin Kuttawa,\nHope Yates, of Marion was here\nSunday, admiring the town?\nT. J. Ordway and II. C. Rice\nwcro in Slaughtervillc last week on\nbusiness.\nMrs. Ida Stone, of Marion, spent\nSunday with her parents, Rev. and\nMrs. W. N. Rcid.\nFine Hay lor Sale.\nTon tons ba